snippet.textDisplay:
i mean... it isn’t “just greed” that would lead an artist to seek recognition that their own art and ideas have been plagiarized.

remember when you criticized that book that rewrote famous vines in a fancy font ? it’s so similar to this situation. the author writing that book didn’t cause you to lose money, but it still felt (and was) wrong, because it was not their idea and yet they were profiting from it.

in a case of music plagiarism, a band may not lose listeners because of another artist copying their music, but the copycat is making money by abusing a composition, an idea, a “catchy melody”, if you will, that isn’t their own.

i’m not even talking about juice world and yellowcard, by the way. i mean it in a general way
snippet.textOriginal:
i mean... it isn’t “just greed” that would lead an artist to seek recognition that their own art and ideas have been plagiarized. 

remember when you criticized that book that rewrote famous vines in a fancy font ? it’s so similar to this situation. the author writing that book didn’t cause you to lose money, but it still felt (and was) wrong, because it was not *their* idea and yet they were profiting from it. 

in a case of music plagiarism, a band may not lose listeners because of another artist copying their music, but the copycat *is* making money by abusing a composition, an idea, a “catchy melody”, if you will, that isn’t their own.

i’m not even talking about juice world and yellowcard, by the way. i mean it in a general way
